Water intake was not different among treatments (P
 = 0.47;
Figure 4). As shown in Figure 4, when calves began weaning at wk 6, more water was consumed among treatments during wk 7 and 8 compared with the preweaning week. This is in contrast to a study by Guindon et al. (2015), which found that calves fed up to 1.1 kg DM of MR daily consumed 1.6 times the amount of water compared with calves fed 0.44 kg DM of MR daily. Those authors attributed the difference to the nutrient density being greater in the high-protein MR (17% solids) and likely causing an osmolality effect that, combined with greater tissue accretion, may have driven calves to drink more water. Calves on the current study consumed less MR and the MR was reconstituted to only 13% solids.
